// AUTO-GENERATED ASSET — do not edit by hand.
//
// Packaged-app startup splash animation, embedded as a base64 `data:` URL so it
// is compiled straight into the desktop main bundle. We intentionally inline it
// instead of shipping a loose file: the desktop runtime resolves no reliable
// on-disk asset path inside the packaged `.app` (the existing icon lookup in
// runtime.ts already falls back to null there), so a filesystem asset would not
// render in production. Inlining guarantees identical behaviour in dev and in
// packaged builds with zero electron-builder file-inclusion wiring.
//
// Provenance: user-provided replacement startup animation. The clip is ~1.7s
// and is used as the one-shot splash video; the <video> freezes on its final
// frame while the web runtime finishes booting.
//
// The clip has a TRANSPARENT background (VP9 alpha). The splash window and its
// <video> are white (#ffffff), so the white shows through — do NOT flatten the
// alpha onto black during re-encode or the splash turns black (see runtime.ts
// `createPendingHtml`). The `-pix_fmt yuva420p` flag below is what preserves it.
//
// To regenerate from a transparent source webm SRC, compress deterministically:
// ffmpeg -y -c:v libvpx-vp9 -i SRC -an -c:v libvpx-vp9 -pix_fmt yuva420p \
//   -crf 60 -b:v 0 -deadline good -cpu-used 4 -row-mt 1 splash-compressed.webm
// Then base64-encode splash-compressed.webm without line wraps and paste it
// into SPLASH_VIDEO_DATA_URL below.

export const SPLASH_VIDEO_DATA_URL = "data:video/webm;base64,";
